                <td bgcolor="#000000" valign="top"><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;04/30/2003&nbsp;: 2:52:48 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> I SPAM /pet back off as I run back to my pet, and pull with line of sight aggro as I am KoS.  Getting KoS and run1 aids you immensely while pulling.<br /><br />Back bridge guards I can ONLY split approaching them from the bard's side (left) so that only the far one can see me, casting max range nullify, and staying still a second so he doesn't swing back and aggro his partner.<br /><br />Sometimes the wanderers Jassong and Mystan are simply too darn close to single without a lot of luck and one standing on a pause-point without line of sight.  If you have a spawn with troublesome spacing, pull the guards all the way back beyond Felwithe Fish House.  The extra few seconds they take to aggro from the right wanderer path is hopefully time to lifetap the current guard to walking away.<br /><br />I often trip the skellie's /shield ability here on a bad, en***bered, got stunned along the way pull--if you can figure out how to do that consistently, let me know.  Skellie regens faster than I do.<br /><br />THANK YOU for figuring out about the level difference of a dualwielder.<br /><br />Speculation about the lifetap dot. . .You FD with a lifetap dot on, let it run out like a good necro. . .THEN /quit.  Is that the mysterious trigger that makes you stand up after /q?<br /><br />Oh, and get another necro while you do this if you're 52 or below.  Two skellies equals twice the bashing power, you can demem Splurt in favor of a lifetap, adds become almost trivial, and when we tried this at level 51 we killed exactly twice as many guards as before, so there was no loss in loot.</span></font></td>
